{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7ebfe13d-2d19-41f8-af2c-144e977586c3","content":"Your code already uses `IFileSystem` from `System.IO.Abstractions`, and `FileSystem` is its built-in real implementation. Could you clarify what kind of wrapper you're looking for? For example:\n\n1. **Decorator** — wraps `IFileSystem` to add logging, error handling, or caching\n2. **Simplified facade** — a smaller interface exposing only the file operations you actually use\n3. **Test fake** — an in-memory implementation for unit tests\n\nWhat do you have in mind?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3a5e3637-b6b0-4d83-a20f-f34fe98f51fd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has a simple .NET project using `System.IO.Abstractions`. They want a file system wrapper. But what exactly do they mean by \"file system wrapper\"? \n\nLooking at the code, they're already using `IFileSystem` from `System.IO.Abstractions` - that IS the abstraction. A \"wrapper\" in this context likely means a custom wrapper/adapter class that wraps `System.IO.Abstractions.IFileSystem` or the real `System.IO` classes to implement `IFileSystem`.\n\nActually, `System.IO.Abstractions` already provides `FileSystem` as the real implementation. So what wrapper would they need?\n \nMaybe they're looking for something that adds logging, caching, or other cross-cutting concerns on top of `IFileSystem`? Or perhaps they want a simpler, more focused interface that wraps the existing abstraction? Let me re-read their request - they say their code already uses `IFileSystem` everywhere and they want a wrapper generated. That's a bit circular since `System.IO.Abstractions.FileSystem` already implements `IFileSystem` and delegates to the real file system.\n\nWithout knowing exactly what they're trying to accomplish - whether it's adding functionality, simplifying the interface, or creating a test double - I should ask them to clarify what kind of wrapper they need.","outputTokens":551,"requestId":"7C1E:283B